OISD Standard GS-1: Gas Detection and Alarm Systems in Petroleum Industry
Section 3.1.8 — Shift Handover Procedures and Gas Readings

Shift handover is a critical safety activity that shall include a comprehensive review of all gas detection readings, alarm histories, and ongoing monitoring activities. The outgoing shift supervisor is responsible for communicating all relevant gas monitoring data to the incoming shift supervisor before any handover is considered complete.

3.1.8.1 MANDATORY HANDOVER CHECKLIST — GAS MONITORING: The following information shall be formally communicated at every shift handover:
(a) Current gas readings at all fixed detector locations, including any readings that have been elevated above baseline in the preceding eight hours;
(b) Any portable gas detector alarms recorded during the shift, with location, time, gas type, concentration, and corrective action taken;
(c) Status of all gas detectors — operational, in maintenance, bypassed, or failed;
(d) Any gas detectors that are bypassed, the reason for bypass, and the compensatory measures in place;
(e) All active hot work permits in hazardous areas and the associated continuous gas monitoring requirements.

3.1.8.2 If any H2S reading above 5 ppm has been recorded at any fixed or portable detector during the shift, this MUST be highlighted as a Priority-1 item in the handover log. The incoming shift supervisor shall personally verify current H2S readings at the noted locations before assuming site responsibility.

3.1.8.3 The handover process shall not be considered complete unless both outgoing and incoming supervisors have signed the handover log, confirming receipt of all gas monitoring data. A running log of gas readings shall be maintained for the previous 72 hours and be immediately accessible to all supervisors.

3.1.8.4 Failure to complete a proper gas monitoring handover constitutes a violation of this standard and shall be treated as a safety non-compliance event requiring reporting to the site safety officer.

