OISD Standard GS-1: Gas Detection and Alarm Systems in Petroleum Industry
Section 6.3 — Hot Work in Hazardous Areas

Hot work is defined as any operation involving open flame, spark generation, arc welding, grinding, or any other ignition source. In hazardous areas of petroleum installations, hot work is a high-risk activity that requires formal authorization through the permit-to-work system.

6.3.1 PRE-HOT WORK REQUIREMENTS: Before any hot work permit is issued in a hazardous area, the following conditions must all be verified and documented:
(a) Gas testing confirms LEL < 10% and H2S < 5 ppm at the work location and within 15 metres;
(b) All process equipment within 15 metres has been depressurized, purged, and isolated;
(c) Firefighting equipment (minimum one 9 kg dry powder extinguisher + one 45-litre foam trolley or equivalent) is positioned at the work site;
(d) A fire watch person has been designated, who holds no other duty during hot work;
(e) All drains, trenches, and low-lying areas within 10 metres have been sealed or water-sealed to prevent vapor accumulation;
(f) The hot work permit has been signed by the Performing Authority and independently verified by the Area Authority;
(g) All workers at the hot work site have been briefed on the emergency evacuation route and muster point.

6.3.2 CONTINUOUS MONITORING DURING HOT WORK: Gas monitoring shall be continuous throughout all hot work activities. If at any time during hot work the LEL reading rises above 10% or H2S rises above 5 ppm, work shall STOP immediately and the area shall be evacuated pending investigation and clearance.

6.3.3 MAXIMUM DURATION: Hot work permits are valid for a maximum of 8 hours (one shift). A permit cannot be extended — a new permit with fresh gas testing must be issued for work continuing into the next shift.

