SAFE WORK PRINCIPLES — RESPIRATORY PROTECTION
SCBA (Self-Contained Breathing Apparatus) Deployment Thresholds and Use Requirements

Self-Contained Breathing Apparatus (SCBA) provides the highest level of respiratory protection by supplying clean breathing air from a self-contained cylinder, independent of the ambient atmosphere. SCBA is required in immediately dangerous to life and health (IDLH) atmospheres and in rescue situations.

SCBA DEPLOYMENT THRESHOLDS:

MANDATORY SCBA USE — Conditions requiring SCBA before entry:
(a) H2S ≥ 10 ppm (IDLH per NIOSH; habitual limit for SCBA per OISD-GS-1);
(b) CO ≥ 200 ppm;
(c) O2 < 16% (immediately life-threatening oxygen deficiency);
(d) LEL ≥ 25% (explosive atmosphere combined with potential ignition sources);
(e) Any atmosphere where the toxic agent is unknown or unquantified;
(f) All confined space rescue operations regardless of gas readings;
(g) Firefighting and fire suppression operations.

SCBA STANDBY REQUIREMENTS: During hot work or confined space entry where SCBA is not being worn continuously but gas hazards are present, SCBA sets shall be placed in ready-to-don condition at: within 10 metres of the work point for coke oven areas (per DGMS Circular 2021-03); within 15 metres of the work point for other hazardous areas.

SCBA INSPECTION AND MAINTENANCE: SCBA shall be inspected before each use. Full cylinder should contain ≥ 90% of rated capacity (pressure check). Mask seal shall be positive-pressure tested before entry. SCBA shall be serviced per manufacturer specifications at minimum every 12 months. Air cylinders shall be hydrostatically tested per statutory requirements (typically every 3-5 years).

DURATION AND LIMITATION: Most industrial SCBA units provide 30-45 minutes of air at moderate work rates. In hot environments or physically demanding tasks, actual duration may be significantly reduced. Work tasks in SCBA shall be planned with a 25% time margin for safe egress.

