SAFE WORK PRINCIPLES — HOT WORK MANAGEMENT
Fire Watch Requirements and Responsibilities During and After Hot Work

The Fire Watch is a dedicated safety role during hot work operations. The fire watch person is responsible for monitoring conditions during and after hot work to ensure early detection of any fire or gas hazard.

FIRE WATCH DUTIES DURING HOT WORK:
(a) Position themselves to have clear visibility of the hot work area and all surfaces that could receive sparks, spatter, or heat;
(b) Monitor gas detector readings continuously — must be equipped with a functioning multi-gas detector;
(c) Have firefighting equipment immediately accessible and know how to use it;
(d) Be in direct communication with the hot work operator at all times;
(e) Have authority to stop work immediately if any unsafe condition is identified;
(f) NOT perform any other duties while acting as fire watch — this is a dedicated role.

POST-HOT WORK FIRE WATCH: After hot work is completed, fire watch shall continue for a minimum period based on work type: (a) arc welding or cutting: 60 minutes post-work; (b) grinding or disc cutting: 30 minutes post-work; (c) gas welding or torch cutting: 60 minutes post-work. This requirement cannot be waived. Spontaneous ignition of smoldering material is a documented cause of fires discovered hours after hot work completion.

GAS MONITORING DURING FIRE WATCH: Gas monitoring shall be continuous during the post-work fire watch period. If LEL exceeds 5% or H2S exceeds 5 ppm at any time during the post-work watch period, the fire watch person shall immediately alert the area supervisor and initiate evacuation of non-essential personnel.
